<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-307-296  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 307 296.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Jan 16 1989 v3 n3 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computers analyze greenhouse effect; federal agencies join forcesin modeling cause and effect of climate changes.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Palmer, Scott D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The President's Committee on Earth Sciences will coordinate theresearch efforts of several government agencies involved in thetask of analyzing the greenhouse effect of global warming thatthreatens the Earth's environment.andP;  Among the agencies mostinvolved in using computer modeling technologies to study the'greenhouse effect' are NASA, the National Oceanic and AtmosphericAdministration, the National Science Foundation, the EnvironmentalProtection Agency and the Department of Energy.andP;  The Committee onEarth Sciences was founded by Bill Graham, President Reagan'sscience advisor, to coordinate the activities of the variousagencies and their budgets in this area.andP;  Some claim the modelingtools are intended as research and teaching tools and areinappropriate for setting policy.andP;  The activities of severalgovernment agencies doing research into the problem of globalwarming are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Environmental ProtectionGovernment AgencyNational GovernmentModelingMeteorologyNew TechniqueScientific ResearchUnited States. President's Committee on Earth SciencesGreenhouse effect, Atmospheric.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>